Article.Abstract: We recently described human leukocyte antigen (HLA) A2, A3 and B7 supertypes, characterized by largely overlapping peptide-binding specificities and represented in a high percentage of different populations. Here, we identified 17 Plasmodium falciparum peptides capable of binding these supertypes and assessed antigenicity in both vaccinated and naturally exposed populations. Positive cytotoxic T lymphocyte recall and cytokine (interferon-gamma and tumor necrosis factor alpha) responses were detected for all peptides; all were recognized in the context of more than one HLA class I molecule; and at least 12 of the 17 were recognized in the context of all HLA alleles studied. These data validate the concept of HLA supertypes at the biological level, show that highly degenerate peptides are almost always recognized as epitopes, and demonstrate the feasibility of developing a universally effective vaccine by focusing on a limited number of peptide specificities.
Article.ArticleTitle: Degenerate cytotoxic T cell epitopes from P. falciparum restricted by multiple HLA-A and HLA-B supertype alleles.
Article.Affiliations: Malaria Program, Naval Medical Research Institute, Bethesda, Maryland 20889-5670, USA.

FirstInVivoProcess.DoseSchedule: Exposed to P. falciparum infected mosquitoe bites during 9-14 sessions over 23 months

Immunization.ImmunizationComments: Volunteers were exposed to the bites of γ-irradiated Anopheles stephensi mosquitoes infected by P. falciparum NF54 or 3D7 during 9-14 sessions over a period of 23 months. PBMC were cultured with 10 µg/ml of the peptide for 7 days. Human rIL-2 was added 2 days after initiation of the culture.

AssayInformation.AssayComments: Similar results were observed for cytokine TNF-α or IFN-γ responses.

Immunization.ImmunizationComments: PBMC were collected from subjects of malaria endemic region with HLA-A2<sup>+</sup> by serological typing. They reported an average of 2.1 episodes of clinical malaria within the previous year. Sixteen of the 85 subjects were parasitemic, and 26% of them were positive for HIV-1 or HIV-2.

AssayInformation.AssayComments: Similar results were observed for cytokine TNF-α and CTL responses.

PBMC were cultured with 10 µg/ml of the peptide for 7 days. Human rIL-2 was added 2 days after initiation of the culture.

AssayInformation.AssayComments: Similar results were observed for cytokine TNF-α or IFN-γ responses.

Immunization.ImmunizationComments: PBMC were collected from subjects of malaria endemic region with HLA-A2<sup>+</sup> by serological typing. They reported an average of 2.1 episodes of clinical malaria within the previous year. Sixteen of the 85 subjects were parasitemic, and 26% of them were positive for HIV-1 or HIV-2.

AssayInformation.AssayComments: Similar results were observed for cytokine TNF-α and CTL responses.
